{"bgColorIndex":0,"textColorIndex":1,"note":"\n\n\nchown - to change the owner of a file or directory\nchown <new owner> <the file>\n\nchown -R = to change the owner of a director and everything inside it\nchown -R <new owner> <the directory>\n\nll or ls -l\n\n\nsu = means “switch user”\n\n\n\nchmod = change mode\n  u - user\n  g - group\n  o - others\n  a - all of the above\n\n  - = to remove permission\n  + = to add permission\n  = = to set a permission and remove others\n\n\n  r = read permission\n  w = write permission\n  x = execute permission\n\n\nchmod g+w <filename> = add write permission for a group and its members\nchmod a-w <filename> = remove write permission for everyone\nchmod a-rwx <filename> = remove read, write, execute permission for everyone\nchmod a=w <filename> = gives only write permission to everyone\nchmod ug+w <filename> = gives write permission to both the user and group\n\n\n\noctal binary filemode\n\n0      000     ——-\n\n1      001     —-x\n\n2      010     -w-\n\n3      011     -wx\n\n4      100     r—-\n\n5      101     r-w\n\n6      110     rw-\n\n7      111     rwx\n\n\n\nread = r = 4\nwrite = w = 2\nexecute = x = 1\n\nrwx = 7\nr-x = 5\nr— = 4\nrw- = 6\n—-x = 1\n——- = 0\n\nsudo hostnamectl set-hostname <new hostname> = to change hostname\n\numask value is used to set the permissions a file or directory will have at creation. its good for file security.\n\ncommand to check the umask = umask\ncommand to set new umask = umask <new value>\n\ncp = copy command \n\ncp <current filename> <new copy name>\n\nto search for a file or directory\n\nfind ~ -name <filename>\n\nsudo timedatectl set-timezone <new timezone> = to change hostname\n\n\n\nsu - <username> = switch user\n\nto assign a password\n\nsudo passwd <username>\n\nto add a user\n\nsudo useradd <username>\n\nto grant a user a sudo access\n\nsudo vi \/etc\/sudoers\n\nto delete a user\n\nsudo userdel <username>\n\nto delete a user and the home directory\n\nsudo userdel -r  <username>\n\nto modify a user accounts\n\nsudo usermod\n\nto add a group\n\nsudo groupadd <groupname>\n\nto check if a user has been created\ncat \/etc\/passwd\nor\ngrep <username> \/etc\/password\nor\nid <username>\n\nto check if a user has password\nsudo cat \/etc\/shadow\nsudo grep <username> \/etc\/shadow\n\nto add a user to a group\n\nsudo usermod -aG managers <username>\n\nto check available groups\n\ncat \/etc\/group \ntail -5 \/etc\/group\n\nto lock a user account\n\nsudo passwd -l <username>\n\nto unlock a user account\n\nsudo passwd -u <username>\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"}